    <section id="heritage">
        <h2>Heritage Sites</h2>
        <div class="heritage-container">
            <div class="heritage-item">
                <img src="amber-fort-2.jpg" alt="Amber Fort" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Amber Fort</h3>
                    <p>An iconic fort located in Jaipur, known for its artistic style elements.Amer Fort or Amber Fort is a fort located in Amer, Rajasthan, India. Amer is a town with an area of 4 square kilometres (1.5 sq mi)[2] located 11 kilometres (6.8 mi) from Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan. Located high on a hill, it is the principal tourist attraction in Jaipur.[3][4] Amer Fort is known for its artistic style elements. With its large ramparts and series of gates and cobbled paths, the fort overlooks Maota Lake,[4][5][6][7] which is the main source of water for the Amer Palace.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="heritage-item">
                <img src="Mehrangarh-Fort_18th-oct.jpg" alt="Mehrangarh Fort" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Mehrangarh Fort</h3>
                    <p>One of the largest forts in India, located in Jodhpur.Mehrangarh Fort, located in Jodhpur, Rajasthan, is one of the largest and most impressive forts in India. It stands 400 feet (122 meters) above the city and is surrounded by thick, imposing walls. Built in 1459 by Rao Jodha, the founder of Jodhpur, Mehrangarh has witnessed centuries of history and is a testament to the grandeur of Rajput architecture and culture.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="heritage-item">
                <img src="Hawa-Mahal.jpg" alt="Hawa Mahal" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Hawa Mahal</h3>
                    <p>The Palace of Winds is a must-visit place in Jaipur.Hawa Mahal, or the "Palace of Winds," is a stunning five-story palace located in the heart of Jaipur, Rajasthan. Built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh, the palace is one of the most iconic landmarks of Jaipur and a brilliant example of Rajput architecture, blending both Hindu and Islamic styles.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Wildlife Section -->
    <section id="wildlife">
        <h2>Wildlife Sanctuaries</h2>
        <div class="wildlife-container">
            <div class="wildlife-item">
                <img src="Ranthambore-Tiger-Reserve.jpg" alt="Ranthambore National Park" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Ranthambore National Park</h3>
                    <p>Best known for its tigers and safari tours.Ranthambore National Park, located in the Sawai Madhopur district of Rajasthan, is one of the most renowned wildlife sanctuaries in India. Covering an area of 1,334 square kilometers, it is famous for its population of Bengal tigers and is one of the best places in India to see these majestic animals in their natural habitat.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="wildlife-item">
                <img src="male-indian-tiger-ranthambore-india-1024x768.jpg" alt="Sariska Tiger Reserve" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Sariska Tiger Reserve</h3>
                    <p>Popular tiger reserve nestled in the Aravalli Hills.Sorsan Grasslands, also known as Sarai-Ka-Sanctuary, is located in the Baran district of Rajasthan, and it is a lesser-known wildlife sanctuary that primarily protects grassland ecosystems. The sanctuary is an important habitat for a variety of wildlife species, including birds, mammals, and reptiles, and is particularly significant for being a haven for the Great Indian Bustard, a critically endangered bird species.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Festivals Section -->
    <section id="festivals">
        <h2>Festivals of Rajasthan</h2>
        <div class="festival-container">
            <div class="festival-item">
                <img src="Fair-and-Festivals-of-Rajasthan.jpg" alt="Pushkar Camel Fair" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Pushkar Camel Fair</h3>
                    <p>A cultural spectacle showcasing thousands of camels and vibrant folk traditions.The Pushkar Festival, also known as the Pushkar Camel Fair, is an annual event held in the town of Pushkar, Rajasthan. It is one of the largest and most famous fairs in India, drawing in thousands of tourists, pilgrims, and traders from across the world. The festival typically takes place in November during the Hindu month of Kartik (on the full moon day, known as Kartik Purnima), lasting for around five to seven days.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="festival-item">
                <img src="74623_Reuters-Mehendi.jpg" alt="teej" width="500" height="400">
                <div class="text-container">
                    <h3>Teej</h3>
                    <p>A popular festival in Rajasthan.Teej Festival is a major celebration in Rajasthan, deeply rooted in cultural and religious traditions. It primarily honors the reunion of the Hindu goddess Parvati with her consort, Lord Shiva. Teej is a celebration of monsoon, marital bliss, and women's well-being and is observed with great enthusiasm by married women who pray for their husbands' long lives and happiness.</p>
                </div>
                </div>
                <div class="festival-item">
                    <img src="16536469081082530791.jpg" alt="Gangaur" width="500" height="400">
                    <div class="text-container">
                        <h3>Gangaur</h3>
                        <p>A Biggest festival celebrated in Rajasthan.Gangaur Festival is one of the most significant and widely celebrated festivals in Rajasthan, dedicated to Goddess Gauri, an incarnation of Parvati, and her consort, Lord Shiva. The festival, which symbolizes marital bliss, love, and prosperity, is especially important for married women, who pray for the well-being of their husbands and happiness in married life. Unmarried women also participate, praying for a good husband.

                            The word "Gangaur" is derived from "Gan," referring to Lord Shiva, and "Gaur," referring to Goddess Parvati. The festival typically takes place in the month of Chaitra (March-April), right after the Holi festival, and is observed for 18 days.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>



